utch: from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stier</i>, German <i>Stier</i> ‘bull, bullock’, hence a nickname for someone thought to resemble the animal in some way or a metonymic occupational name for someone who tended cattle. This surname is rare in the Netherlands."]}]},{"name":"Stie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian: variant of   Stigen  .","German and Flemish: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Augustin</i>, Dutch <i>Augustijn</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Stiens","meanings":["German and Flemish: patronymic from the personal name   Stien  ."]},{"name":"Stigen","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads named from the definite singular of <i>stig</i>, Old Norse <i>stígr</i> ‘path’, ‘trail’, frequently denoting a position high on a hillside."]}]},{"name":"Greger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Gregory</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gregers","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Gregory</b> ."]},{"name":"Gregory","meanings":["Via Latin <i>Gregorius</i> from the post-classical Greek name <i>Gregōrios</i> ‘watchful’ (a derivative of <i>gregōrein</i> ‘to watch, be vigilant’). The name was a very popular one among the early Christians, who were mindful of the injunction ‘be sober, be vigilant’ (1 Peter 5:8). It was borne by a number of early saints. The most important, in honour of whom the name was often bestowed from medieval times onwards, were Gregory of Nazianzen (  <i>c.</i>329–90 ), Gregory of Nyssa (  d. <i>c.</i>395 ), Gregory of Tours (  538–94 ), and  Pope Gregory the Great  (  <i>c.</i>540–604 ). A famous bearer of the name in modern times is the film star  Gregory Peck  (  1916–2003 ). The name has traditionally been popular in Scotland, where it is often found in the form  <b>Gregor</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Greger N